  "findings": [
    {
      "id": "ARCH-001",
      "reviewer": "architecture",
      "severity": "P1",
      "classification": "NEW",
      "file": "docs/v1.4.2-plan.md",
      "line": 86,
      "evidence": "docs/v1.4.2-plan.md:86-94 says .bootstrap.yaml holds conduct.mcp_policy and conduct.mcp_allowlist, and lines 96-99 add conduct.sh flags/default clean. However the implementation impact section only assigns commands/bs.md to B2/C1/C2 at line 174, not A3, and the test plan at line 193 only asserts conduct.sh parsing. Current commands/bs.md:35 invokes conduct.sh with no binding-derived MCP policy, current contract.md binding requirements at lines 19-27 do not document a conduct section, and bundle/bootstrap.yaml.template:1-39 has no conduct defaults.",
      "failure_mode": "A repo can configure conduct.mcp_policy: full or allowlist as the plan promises, but /bs has no planned command-contract wiring to read that binding and pass --mcp-policy/--mcp-allow to conduct.sh. Since conduct.sh defaults to clean, such repos silently run with MCP/skills suppressed; tasks that require an allowed/full MCP environment fail even though the binding appears valid and reviewable.",
      "recommendation": "Add A3 wiring to the plan: contract.md documents optional conduct.mcp_policy/mcp_allowlist, bundle/bootstrap.yaml.template includes defaults, lib/binding.py validates the enum/list, commands/bs.md reads the binding snapshot and passes --mcp-policy/--mcp-allow to conduct.sh, and tests cover binding-to-conduct propagation, not just shell flag parsing.",
      "confidence": 0.94
    },
    {
      "id": "COR-001",
      "reviewer": "correctness",
      "severity": "P2",
      "classification": "NEW",
      "file": "docs/v1.4.2-plan.md",
      "line": 217,
      "evidence": "A1 now correctly states that item/agentMessage/delta must not disarm the first-work-item gate at docs/v1.4.2-plan.md:50 and acceptance line 62. The risk table still says any item/* including message delta disarms it at line 217.",
      "failure_mode": "The frozen plan contains contradictory implementation guidance for the exact prior correctness bug. An implementer following the risk table can reintroduce the old text-delta disarm behavior while still claiming the plan was followed.",
      "recommendation": "Change the risk-table mitigation to say only a real work item, such as item/started, item/completed, or fileChange, disarms the gate; text/model-output deltas may be diagnostic only.",
      "confidence": 0.9
    }
  ],
